This is the (node.js) code I'm using to query (from a simple datastore with just a single entity):

Datastore = require('@google-cloud/datastore');
projectId = '<my-project-id>';

datastoreClient = Datastore({
  projectId: projectId
});

var query = datastoreClient.createQuery('Test').limit(1);

console.time('query');
query.run(function (err, test) {
  if (err) {
    console.log(err);
    return;
  }
  console.timeEnd('query');
});

The first request takes > 2 sec and the subsequent requests are still faster.
If you wait 4 minutes or more between requests, query times are back to >2 secs.

SCSS and `@extend` are wildly troublesome when used with classnames because they extend any instances where the target is the last piece of a selector. Now that you're using the following on line 109 of `_navs.scss`:

    &.nav-justified {
      @extend .nav-justified;
      @extend .nav-tabs-justified;
    }

And we use the following in our own scss:

`.nav-tabs:not(.nav-justified) { ... }`

The compiled output is:

`.nav-tabs:not(.nav-justified):not(.nav-tabs.nav-justified) { ... }`

Which is invalid CSS and breaks our styling.

When commenting out line 109 in your file, it becomes:

`.nav-tabs:not(.nav-justified)`

If you're intending to *share* styles within your own scss, I would highly advise using a placeholder so you don't copy unwanted styles, especially since this project is intended to allow for custom compilation by users.

*Edit: Now that I review your history though, it's been this way since 2013. This is how `@extend` behaves so it's a valid complaint. I have to assume that it's only now compiling incorrectly because of a sass update.

I’ve been hacking on trying to get extra jars with classifiers supported throughout pants. I ran into problems in several places. I’ve got goal idea patched up (but not all problems resolved). There is an issue with the export format (For IDE plugins) which currently looks like this:

```
 "libraries": { 
        "org.hamcrest:hamcrest-core:1.3": { 
            "default": "/Users/zundel/.ivy2/pants/org.hamcrest/hamcrest-core/jars/hamcrest-core-1.3.jar" 
        }, 
        "org.slf4j:slf4j-api:1.6.1": { 
            "default": "/Users/zundel/.ivy2/pants/org.slf4j/slf4j-api/jars/slf4j-api-1.6.1.jar" 
        }, 
       ...
    },
```

The issue is that there are multiple jars returned in cases like the one Mike pointed out above. Internally, I’ve changed some of the parsing to return a list instead of a single jar file. The simplest approach would be to do this in the export format:

```
 "libraries": {
        "com.example:foo:1.2.3": {
            "default": [ "/Users/zundel/.ivy2/pants/com.example/foo/foo.1.2.3.jar",  "/Users/zundel/.ivy2/pants/com.example/foo/foo-extra.1.2.3.jar" ]
        },
```

I thought about just appending an arbitrary uniqifier to the end of the key field in libraries, but these keys are referenced in target dependencies later in the file.

I think the problem propagates all the way through pants.  If separate `JarDependency` queries were used to represent the request for jars with classifiers, then we could have the key specified in the dependency, then the key would resolve to a single jar we could tag in the libraries section.

The unique coordinates for a maven artifact are:

groupId:artifactId:version:packaging:classifier

or in Ivy/Pants terminology:

org:name:rev:type_:classifier

(The last two fields are optional)

(See https://maven.apache.org/pom.html#Maven_Coordinates)

Currently, we only use `org:name:rev` in the export format.  Also, we are not propagating the entire key through to the 'ivy_jar_products' product.   The key in that product is `IvyModuleRef`. Maybe it would be better if we described both the JarDependency key and key in `ivy_jar_products` with a full set of maven coordinates.

